      soil moisture and forest conditions to determine the probability
      and location of wild fires.

      Geographic data is key to coordinating the response to a wild
      fire across agencies and juristictions.

      During the 2015 Forest fire near Kosapechekanesik, the provice of
      Manitoba turned to Pacific Geomatics to source satellite imagery
      that could guide responders to actve burn sites.

      Working with its satellite imagery partners Pacific Geomatics
      assembled imagery of the effected area to create a dataset
      multi-spectrum data-set to enable analysis.

      In the visible spectrum imagery the burn sites were obsured by
      clouds. The near infra-red "false colour" image shows the flames
      better than the true colour image.

      But the real actionable information is revealed via the Short
      Wave Infra-Red imagery, which penetrates the smoke to reveal the
      active burn sites clearly.
